A health care worker is pictured at a vaccination site in Germiston, South Africa in May 2021 PRETORIA - South Africa's President Cyril Ramaphosa on Sunday reimposed restrictions for two weeks to combat a surge in the highly contagious coronavirus Delta variant. SA "is facing a massive resurgence of infection," the president said in a televised address to the nation. READ: SA Lockdown: South Africa moves to alert level 4 "Our health facilities are stretched to the limit... ICU beds are in short supply," he said as he placed the country on an adjusted alert level four. Ramaphosa banned all gatherings, except for funerals where numbers will be capped at 50, and also ordered a ban on the sale of alcohol.  DA leader John Steenhuisen reacts to SA moving to adjusted Level 4 Lockdown #DStv403 #eNCA Eateries and restaurants will not be allowed to serve sit-down meals, and will only be allowed to sell food for take-away or delivery. A nighttime curfew has been lengthened by an hour - starting at 9pm till 4am, while all schools should be shut by Friday. Authorities say the peak of the third wave -- fuelled by the Delta variant first identified in India -- will surpass that of earlier waves as the country struggles to quickly roll out vaccinations. READ: Delta variant dominating SA third wave "We are in the grip of a devastating wave that by all indications seems like it will be worse than those that preceded it," Ramaphosa said. South Africa now counts 1,928,897 coronavirus cases after recording 15,036 new cases on Sunday, a drop from the previous day when 18,762 new infections were diagnosed. eNCA's Shahan Ramkissoon and Faith Mangope speaks to professor Mosa Moshabela from University of KwaZulu-Natal following President Cyril Ramaphosa's announcement that the country will move to adjusted alert level 4 on Monday. #DStv403 The COVID-19 death toll stands at 59,900. Leisure travel in and out of the densely populated province of Gauteng -- encompassing Johannesburg and Pretoria, the nation's economic and industrial heartland -- has been outlawed. The province which accounts for around 60 percent of national infections, has become the epicentre of the outbreak. The country's vaccination drive has been slow. Around 2.7 million people have been immunised since February, but Ramaphosa said the inoculation exercise has gained momentum. The Delta variant is causing havoc in South Africa. This highly infectious Delta variant is behind the current surge in new COVID-19 cases. Virologist and Clinical researcher at Numolux Group – Dr. Sanet Aspinal speaks to #eNCA Courtesy #DStv403 Most business will forge ahead operating at full capacity, a move he said was to enable as much economic activity to continue as possible. The economy of Africa's most industrialised country slumped by seven percent in 2020 compared to the previous year. Health officials across the world have been alarmed by the rapid spread of the Delta variant. The World Health Organization said on Friday that the Delta variant had reached at least 85 countries. sn-ten/pvh Lucky Ntimane from the National Liquor Traders Council reacts to the President's address #eNCA Courtesy #DStv403